II.  SUMMARY  3 
Q PLEASE SUMMARIZE YOUR SURREBUTTAL TESTIMONY . 4 
A T he acquisition  proposed by the Joint Applicants (“Proposed Acquisition”)  is entirely 5 
premised upon an outsized capital investment plan.  My testimony explains that the Joint 6 
Applicants have not met their burden of proof to demonstrate the capital investment 7 
plan underpinning the proposed Acquisition is in the public interest.  Instead, the 8 
Partners  have merely shown it is in their interest to invest billions of dollars to drive up 9 
rate base and earn significant projected returns  at the expense of Minnesotans.  T o 10 
achieve their outsized returns, the Partners  need to invest at a pace incomparable to 11 
historic investments , and they assume the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission 12 
(“Commission ”) will authorize their planned investments.  If the Commission instead 13 
slows the projected pace of investments , it is possible, if not likely , the Partners  will 14 
cease investing in Minnesota Power and seek a new buyer so they can invest in more 15 
lucrative endeavors that will yield the return they are projecting in this Proposed 16 
Acquisition.  In either case, customers lose – either via skyrocketing rates or via another 17 
acquisition of Minnesota P ower , with the potential to be riskier than the current 18 
Proposed Acquisition .  The Commission should act now to deny the Application and 19 
protect customers and Minnesotans from the lose/lose situation of unaffordable rates or 20 
another risky and uncertain acquisition.  21 
Christopher C. Walters

BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC. III.  THE PROPROSED TRANSACTION IS NOT IN THE PUBLIC INTEREST  1 
A. The Joint Applicants Haves Not Met The ir Burden of Proof  2 
Q HAVE THE JOINT APPLICANTS  PROVIDED QUANTIFIABLE, TANGIBLE 3 
BENEFITS TO RATEPAYERS THAT WOULD OUTWEIGH THE RISKS AND 4 
JUSTIFY APPROVAL OF THE PROPOSED ACQUISITION? 5 
A No.  Despite multiple opportunities, neither Minnesota Power nor the Partners have 6 
provided any quantifiable analysis, concrete studies, or detailed financial modeling 7 
demonstrating measurable net customer benefits from the proposed transaction.  8 
Instead, their testimonies of all of the representatives of the Joint Applicants continue 9 
to offer generalized assurances of improved capital access and unspecified strategic 10 
alignment, which remain speculative and intangible .  The lack of quantifiable, tangible 11 
benefits to ratepayers, is reiterated in the response to LPI IR 109.1   12 
 
Q WHY IS IT IMPORTANT THAT THE SUPPOSED BENEFITS  OF THE 13 
TRANSACTION BE TANGIBLE AND QUANTIFIABLE ? 14 
A It is critical because the burden of proof rests on the Joint Applicants to show concrete 15 
benefits clearly aligned with the public interest standard required for regulatory 16 
approval.  Without quantifiable evidence of actual customer savings, rate reductions, 17 
operational synergies, or  improved reliability, the Commission cannot reasonably 18 
conclude the transaction provides benefits sufficient to outweigh the inherent risks and 19 
costs .2 20

through access to the capital markets.  Further, I am unaware of the Company having 11

a satisfactory standing in the credit markets .”3   14

capacity. 19

large part by federal legislation enacted in 2021 and 2022, supporting 22

the explosion in implementation of AI and cloud computing 25

whether the merger would satisfy the public interest under NMSA 1978, § 62-6-12, and 4 
concluded the potential harms of the proposed transaction outweighed the benefits.  5

public interest because the potential harms resulting from the proposed t ransaction did 9 
not outweigh its benefits.  There, the a pplicants contended the proposed t ransaction 10

ratepayers), senior management ( “golden parachutes for three PNMR/PNM Executives 12

receive”), and “hundreds of millions to shareholders .”12  However, the NMPRC found 14 
the application glossed over the proposed t ransaction’s “potential risks” and simply 15 
“recast as additional enhanced benefits” those risks rather than making needed 16 
revisions.13  Such harms included concerns with quality -of-service issues and risks for 17 
improper subsidization of non- utility activities.14 18

Dear Commission Members:
I am writing to urge the Commission to reject the proposed acquisition of Minnesota
Power by BlackRock, as outlined in Docket E-015/PA-24-198. 
The purpose of private equity ownership is to maximize returns to shareholders, not to
provide long-term, affordable, and reliable utility service. This business model isfundamentally at odds with the public service mission of a regulated electric utility.
When private equity firms or institutional investors like BlackRock take over critical
infrastructure, the results have consistently been harmful to ratepayers and the publicinterest. A few recent examples illustrate this:
Puerto Rico’s electric grid was handed over to LUMA Energy, a private entity partlybacked by private equity. Since the transition, residents have experienced worseningreliability, increased outages, and rising rates, along with a lack of transparency andaccountability. Public backlash has been significant, including protests over serviceconditions.
In the United Kingdom, decades of utility privatization, especially in electricity, water,and rail, have led to higher consumer prices, outsized investor returns, andunderinvestment in infrastructure, prompting widespread calls for re-nationalization.The privatized model has put profits ahead of public welfare, often leaving consumersto bear the cost of poor service and infrastructure failure.
Closer to home, in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan, residents experienced sharp rateincreases following the purchase of the region’s utility infrastructure by privateinvestors. As profits were funneled to shareholders, local control vanished andaffordability suffered. That experience serves as a stark warning to Minnesotans aboutthe risks of investor-driven utility ownership.
These are not isolated incidents. They are part of a pattern: when private equity or largeinvestment firms take control of utilities, 
costs rise, service often declines, and public input is
sidelined. Minnesota Power is an essential part of the state’s infrastructure and economy,
especially in northern communities. Turning its future over to a global investment firm
accountable only to its shareholders is not in the best interests of Minnesota consumers.
I urge the Commission to reject this acquisition in order to preserve the accountability,
transparency, and public-centered mission of utility service in our state.

the required documents on March 12, 2025.  The record regarding the Motion closed on 
that date.

MEMORANDUM  
 
I. The IC Memos  Were Improperly Redacted.  
CPP- GIP redacted portions of four IC Memos  based on Canadian data- privacy 
law, the attorney work product doctrine,  and the attorney -client privilege . 
A. Canadian Law Does Not Provide a Basis for Redactions.  
As an initial matter, all redactions based on Canadian law are improper. The 
Canadian Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act has no 
applicability in a contested case proceeding pending before this tribunal and the 
Minnesota Public Utilities Commission under Minnesota law.  Furthermore, the Judge has 
[217918/1 ] 3 
 issued a protective order allowing disclosure of dat a covered by applicable law , such as 
the Minnesota Government Data Practices Act.5 Sufficient protections for data of concern 
in the IC Memos is already in place.  
B. The IC  Memos are not Attorney Work Product.  
CPP- GIP makes conclusory assertion s that the redactions were proper ly made  
based on the attorney work product doctrine. To be protected by this  doctrine, material 
must contain opinions, conclusions, legal theories, or mental impressions of counsel, and 
it must have been prepared in anticipation of litigation.6 Whether documents were 
prepared in anticipation of litigation is a factual determinat ion.7 The question is whether, 
in light of the nature of the document and the factual situation in the particular case, the 
document can fairly be said to have been prepared or obtained because of the prospect 
of litigation.8 CPP- GIP’s declaration states that the IC Memos  were “prepared to provide 
a recommendation to the investment committee of CPP Investments as to whether to 
pursue a particular investment .”9 CPP-GIP has not shown that the IC Memos  were 
prepared in anticipation of litigation. The IC Memos are not protected by the work product doctrine.   
C.  The Attorney -Client Privilege P rotects Some of the R edacted Material.  
CPP- GIP claims that the disputed redactions contain legal advice and analysis.  
“The purpose behind the attorney -client privilege is to promote open and honest 
discussion between clients and their attorneys.”
10 Because “the attorney -client privilege 
is a barrier to disclosure and tends to suppress relevant facts,” the privilege  is strictly 
construed.11 The party asserting the privilege has the burden of establishing that the

privilege will protect any portions of the document that contain legal advice. ”15 Legal

(b) commercially sensitive investment, financing, or forward looking business

Minnesotans’ access to the records of the State and its political subdivisions is governed 
by the Minnesota Data Practices Act (the Act).  The Act provides that “ [a]ll government data 
collected, created, received, maintained or disseminated by a government entity shall be public  
unless classified by statute  . . . as nonpublic or protected nonpublic .”5  The presumption that 
government data is public reflects “a fundamental commitment to making the operations of our public institutions open to the public.”
6  As a result , the courts construe the Act in favor of public 
access  to information held by government agencies.7

rade secret data are a type of “nonpublic data” that are exempt from the Act’s public -
disclosure requirement.8  “Trade secret data” means  “government data . . . (1) that was supplied 
by the affected individual or organization, (2) that is the subject of efforts by the individual or organization that are reasonable under the circumstances to maintain its secrecy, and (3) that derives independent economic value, actual or potential, from not being generally known to, and not being readily ascertainable by proper means by, other persons who can obtain economic value from its disclosure or use.”
